10=head1 NAME
11
12IO::Socket::SSL::PublicSuffix - provide access to Mozilla's list of effective TLD names
13
14=head1 SYNOPSIS
15
16 # use builtin default
17 use IO::Socket::SSL::PublicSuffix;
18 $ps = IO::Socket::SSL::PublicSuffix->default;
19
20 # load from string
21 $ps = IO::Socket::SSL::PublicSuffix->from_string("*.uk\n*");
22
23 # load from file or file handle
24 $ps = IO::Socket::SSL::PublicSuffix->from_file($filename);
25 $ps = IO::Socket::SSL::PublicSuffix->from_file(\*STDIN);
26
27
28 # --- string in -> string out
29 # $rest -> whatever.host
30 # $tld -> co.uk
31 my ($rest,$tld) = $ps->public_suffix('whatever.host.co.uk');
32 my $tld = $ps->public_suffix('whatever.host.co.uk');
33
34 # $root_domain -> host.co.uk
35 my $root_domain = $ps->public_suffix('whatever.host.co.uk', 1);
36
37 # --- array in -> array out
38 # $rest -> [qw(whatever host)]
39 # $tld -> [qw(co uk)]
40 my ($rest,$tld) = $ps->public_suffix([qw(whatever host co uk)]);
41
42 ----
43

45 perl -MIO::Socket::SSL::PublicSuffix -e 'IO::Socket::SSL::PublicSuffix::update_self_from_url()'
46

49=head1 DESCRIPTION
50
51This module uses the list of effective top level domain names from the mozilla
52project to determine the public top level domain for a given hostname.
53
54=head2 Method
55
56=over 4
57
58=item class->default(%args)
59
60Returns object with builtin default.
61C<min_suffix> can be given in C<%args> to specify the minimal suffix, default
62is 1.
63
64=item class->from_string(string,%args)
65
66Returns object with configuration from string.
67See method C<default> for C<%args>.
68
69=item class->from_file( file name| file handle, %args )
70
71Returns object with configuration from file or file handle.
72See method C<default> for C<%args>.
73
74=item $self->public_suffix( $host|\@host, [ $add ] )
75
76In array context the function returns the non-tld part and the tld part of the
77given hostname, in scalar context only the tld part.
78It adds C<$add> parts of the non-tld part to the tld, e.g. with C<$add=1> it
79will return the root domain.
80
81If there were no explicit matches against the public suffix configuration it
82will fall back to a suffix of length 1.
83
84The function accepts a string or an array-ref (e.g. host split by C<.>). In the
85first case it will return string(s), in the latter case array-ref(s).
86
87International hostnames or labels can be in ASCII (IDNA form starting with
88C<xn-->) or unicode. In the latter case an IDNA handling library like
89L<Net::IDN:::Encode>, L<Net::LibIDN> or recent versions of L<URI> need to be
90installed.
91
92=item ($self|class)->can_idn
93
94Returns true if IDN support is available.
95
96=back
97
98=head1 FILES
99
100http://publicsuffix.org/list/effective_tld_names.dat
101
102=head1 SEE ALSO
103
104Domain::PublicSuffix, Mozilla::PublicSuffix
105
106=head1 BUGS
107
108 Q: Why yet another module, we already have L<Domain::PublicSuffix> and
109 L<Mozilla::PublicSuffix>.
110 A: Because the public suffix data change more often than these modules do,
111 IO::Socket::SSL needs this list and it is more easy this way to keep it
112 up-to-date.
113
114
115=head1 AUTHOR
116
117Steffen Ullrich
118
119=cut

169sub from_file {
170 my ($class,$file,%args) = @_;
171 my $min_suffix = delete $args{min_suffix};
172 $min_suffix = 1 if ! defined $min_suffix;
173 %args and die "unknown args: ".join(" ",sort keys %args);
174
175 my $fh;

177 $fh = $file
178 } elsif ( ! open($fh,'<',$file)) {
179 die "failed to open $file: $!";
180 }
181 my %tree;
182 local $/ = "\n";
183 while ( my $line = <$fh>) {
184 $line =~s{//.*}{};
185 $line =~s{\s+$}{};
186 $line eq '' and next;
187 my $p = \%tree;
188 $line = idn_to_ascii($line) if $line !~m{\A[\x00-\x7f]*\Z};
189 my $not = $line =~s{^!}{};
190 my @path = split(m{\.},$line);
191 for(reverse @path) {
192 $p = $p->{$_} ||= {}
193 }
194 $p->{'\0'} = $not ? -1:1;
195 }
196 return bless {
197 tree => \%tree,
198 min_suffix => $min_suffix
199 },$class;

203sub public_suffix {
204 my ($self,$name,$add) = @_;
205 my $want; # [a]rray, [s]tring, [u]nicode-string
206 if ( ref($name)) {
207 $want = 'a';
208 $name = [ @$name ]; # don't change input
209 } else {
210 return if ! defined $name;
211 if ( $name !~m{\A[\x00-\x7f]*\Z} ) {
212 $name = idn_to_ascii($name);
213 $want = 'u';
214 } else {
215 $want = 's';
216 }
217 $name = lc($name);
218 $name =~s{\.$}{};
219 $name = [ $name =~m{([^.]+)}g ];
220 }
221 @$name or return;
222 $_ = lc($_) for(@$name);
223
224 my (%wild,%host,%xcept,@stack,$choices);
225 my $p = $self->{tree};
226 for( my $i=0; $i<@$name; $i++ ) {
227 $choices = [];
228 if ( my $px = $p->{ $name->[$#$name-$i] } ) {
229 # name match, continue with next path element
230 push @$choices,$px;
231 if ( my $end = $px->{'\0'} ) {
232 ( $end>0 ? \%host : \%xcept )->{$i+1} = $end;
233 }
234 }
235 if ( my $px = $p->{'*'} ) {
236 # wildcard match, continue with next path element
237 push @$choices,$px;
238 if ( my $end = $px->{'\0'} ) {
239 ( $end>0 ? \%wild : \%xcept )->{$i+1} = $end;
240 }
241 }
242
243
244 next_choice:
245 if ( @$choices ) {
246 $p = shift(@$choices);
247 push @stack, [ $choices, $i ] if @$choices;
248 next; # go deeper
249 }
250
251 # backtrack
252 @stack or last;
253 ($choices,$i) = @{ pop(@stack) };
254 goto next_choice;
255 }
256
257 #warn Dumper([\%wild,\%host,\%xcept]); use Data::Dumper;
258
259
260 # remove all exceptions from wildcards
261 delete @wild{ keys %xcept } if %xcept;
262 # get longest match
263 my ($len) = sort { $b <=> $a } (
264 keys(%wild), keys(%host), map { $_-1 } keys(%xcept));
265 # if we have no matches use a minimum of min_suffix
266 $len = $self->{min_suffix} if ! defined $len;
267 $len += $add if $add;
268 my $suffix;
269 if ( $len < @$name ) {
270 $suffix = [ splice( @$name, -$len, $len ) ];
271 } elsif ( $len > 0 ) {
272 $suffix = $name;
273 $name = []
274 } else {
275 $suffix = []
276 }
277
278 if ( $want ne 'a' ) {
279 $suffix = join('.',@$suffix);
280 $name = join('.',@$name);
281 if ( $want eq 'u' ) {
282 $suffix = idn_to_unicode($suffix);
283 $name = idn_to_unicode($name);
284 }
285 }
286
287 return wantarray ? ($name,$suffix):$suffix;
288}

303sub update_self_from_url {
304 my $url = shift || URL();
305 my $dst = __FILE__;
306 -w $dst or die "cannot write $dst";
307 open( my $fh,'<',$dst ) or die "open $dst: $!";
308 my $code = '';
309 local $/ = "\n";
310 while (<$fh>) {
311 $code .= $_;
312 m{<<\'END_BUILTIN_DATA\'} and last;
313 }
314 my $tail;
315 while (<$fh>) {
316 m{\AEND_BUILTIN_DATA\r?\n} or next;
317 $tail = $_;
318 last;
319 }
320 $tail .= do { local $/; <$fh> };
321 close($fh);
322
323 require LWP::UserAgent;
324 my $resp = LWP::UserAgent->new->get($url)
325 or die "no response from $url";
326 die "no success url=$url code=".$resp->code." ".$resp->message
327 if ! $resp->is_success;
328 my $content = $resp->decoded_content;
329 while ( $content =~m{(.*\n)}g ) {
330 my $line = $1;
331 if ( $line =~m{\S} && $line !~m{\A\s*//} ) {
332 $line =~s{//.*}{};
333 $line =~s{\s+$}{};
334 $line eq '' and next;
335 if ( $line !~m{\A[\x00-\x7f]+\Z} ) {
336 $line = idn_to_ascii($line);
337 }
338 $code .= "$line\n";
339 } else {
340 $code .= "$line";
341 }
342 }
343
344 open( $fh,'>:utf8',$dst ) or die "open $dst: $!";
345 print $fh $code.$tail;
346}
